/*
To find the average, maximum, and minimum values in the data, I use the AVG(), MAX(), and MIN() functions in the SELECT statement. For example, to find the average popularity among all the Marvel characters, you can use the this query:
*/
SELECT AVG(popularity) FROM marvels;



/*
To find the maximum and minimum values, I use MAX() and MIN() functions in a similar way:
*/
SELECT MAX(popularity) FROM marvels;
SELECT MIN(popularity) FROM marvels;



/*
To find the values per category in the data, I use the HAVING clause in the SELECT statement. For example, to find the average popularity for each alignment:
*/
SELECT alignment, AVG(popularity) FROM marvels
GROUP BY alignment
HAVING AVG(popularity) > 0;



/*
This will return the average popularity for each alignment that has at least one Marvel character.
To group data values that do not exist yet, you can use the CASE expression in your SELECT statement. The CASE expression allows you to create a new column that groups
data based on certain conditions. For example, to create a new column that groups Marvel characters as "Strong" or "Not Strong" based on their strength value, you can use 
the following query:
*/
SELECT name, strength,
    CASE
        WHEN strength > 4 THEN 'Strong'
        ELSE 'Not Strong'
    END AS strength_group
FROM marvels;
/*
This will create a new column called "strength_group" that displays either "Strong" or "Not Strong" for each Marvel character.
To filter the data in interesting ways, you can use the AND and OR operators in your WHERE clause. For example, to find all the Marvel characters who are either "Good" or "Neutral"
alignment and have a popularity greater than 10, you can use the following query:
*/



/*
This will return the names, alignments, and popularity of all Marvel characters that meet the specified criteria.
*/
SELECT name, alignment, popularity FROM marvels
WHERE (alignment = 'Good' OR alignment = 'Neutral') AND popularity > 10;

